Short version for non-lawyers:

The Temper Project code is dual-licensed under Apache 2.0 and MIT terms.

The Temper Project documentation is licensed under a Creative Commons
license: CC-BY-SA-4.0.

Both are Copyright (c) The Temper Project Contributors.

Longer version:

Copyrights in the Temper project are retained by their contributors.
No copyright assignment is required to contribute to the Temper
project.

Some files include explicit copyright notices and/or license notices.
For full authorship information, see the version control history.

Except as otherwise noted, Temper is licensed under the Apache
License, Version 2.0 <LICENSE-APACHE> or <https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0>
or the MIT license <LICENSE-MIT> or <https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT>,
at your option.

We track licenses for third-party materials via a `gradle` build tasks
that compile a licenses file which is included in binary distributions
and is available via the Temper command line tool: `temper licenses`.
Please refer to either the file embedded in the binary distribution or
the command line tools replay of it.

The Temper Language Documentation is licensed under the CC-BY-SA 4.0
license <LICENSE-CC-BY-SA-4.0> or <https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/>.
That documentation is assembled from a mixture of hand written
documentation files and comments authored as documentation but
embedded in programming language source files.

Libraries written using the Temper programming language definition, or
its toolchain elements (e.g. the Temper command line tool, the Temper
VSCode plugin, and language server) are the copyright of their
creators and may or may not be licensed in the same way as the Temper
project at the discretion of their creators.
